<InterchangeAssessmentMetadata xmlns="http://ed-fi.org/0100" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://ed-fi.org/0100 ../../sli/common/domain/src/main/resources/edfiXsd/Interchange-AssessmentMetadata.xsd">
    <!-- Circles Learning Standards -->
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-C.1</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Prove that all circles are similar.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-C.2</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Identify and describe relationships among inscribed angles, radii, and chords. Include the relationship between central, inscribed, 
					  and circumscribed angles; inscribed angles on a diameter are right angles; the radius of a circle is perpendicular to the tangent where 
					  the radius intersects the circle.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-C.3</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Construct the inscribed and circumscribed circles of a triangle, and prove properties of angles for a quadrilateral 
					 inscribed in a circle.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-C.4</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>(+) Construct a tangent line from a point outside a given circle to the circle.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-C.5</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Derive using similarity the fact that the length of the arc intercepted by an angle is proportional to the radius, 
					 and define the radian measure of the angle as the constant of proportionality; derive the formula for the area of a sector.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <!-- SRT Learning Standards -->
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.1</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Verify experimentally the properties of dilations given by a center and a scale factor:
					 A dilation takes a line not passing through the center of the dilation to a parallel line, 
					 and leaves a line passing through the center unchanged.
					 The dilation of a line segment is longer or shorter in the ratio given by the scale factor.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.2</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Given two figures, use the definition of similarity in terms of similarity transformations to decide if they are similar; 
					 explain using similarity transformations the meaning of similarity for triangles as the equality of all corresponding pairs of 
					 angles and the proportionality of all corresponding pairs of sides.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.3</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Use the properties of similarity transformations to establish the AA criterion for two triangles to be similar.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.4</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Prove theorems about triangles. Theorems include: a line parallel to one side of a triangle divides the other two proportionally, 
					 and conversely; the Pythagorean Theorem proved using triangle similarity.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.5</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Use congruence and similarity criteria for triangles to solve problems and to prove relationships in geometric figures.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.6</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Understand that by similarity, side ratios in right triangles are properties of the angles in the triangle, 
					 leading to definitions of trigonometric ratios for acute angles.</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.7</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Explain and use the relationship between the sine and cosine of complementary angles.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.8</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>Use trigonometric ratios and the Pythagorean Theorem to solve right triangles in applied problems.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.9</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>(+) Derive the formula A = 1/2 ab sin(C) for the area of a triangle by drawing an auxiliary line from a vertex perpendicular to the 
					opposite side.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.10</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>(+) Prove the Laws of Sines and Cosines and use them to solve problems.
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
    <LearningStandard>
        <LearningStandardId>
            <IdentificationCode>G-SRT.11</IdentificationCode>
        </LearningStandardId>
        <Description>(+) Understand and apply the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines to find unknown measurements in right and non-right triangles 
					 (e.g., surveying problems, resultant forces).
		</Description>
        <ContentStandard>National Standard</ContentStandard>
        <GradeLevel>Twelfth grade</GradeLevel>
        <SubjectArea>Mathematics</SubjectArea>
    </LearningStandard>
